Since the first US death, COVID-19 is average 85/week and that number keeps climbing every day.
It is now surpassing asthma’s weekly average every single day.
Mar 22 deaths = 111 Mar 23 deaths = 140 Mar 24 deaths = 225 Those three days alone are more than 7 weeks of asthma deaths combined.

says: March 27, 2020 at 4:45 am        CDC estimates that the burden of illness during the 2018–2019 season included an estimated 35.5 million people getting sick with influenza, 16.5 million people going to a health care provider for their illness, 490,600 hospitalizations, and 34,200 deaths from influenza 34,200 deaths from the common flu = 657 per week covid 19 got nothing on the common flue yet… says: April 3, 2020 at 8:45 pm        That is for the entire six month flu season.
Because of the way exponential growth of viral diseases work, more than half of the infections occur in the 5th and 6th months of the flu season.
We are two months into COVID-19.
Let’s say COVID-19 only infects 20M.
That is why epidemologists are concerned.
Comparing the raw numbers of a six month flu season to the first two months of COVID-19 mislead people to thinking it’s not as bad.
Using the numbers you provided, flu has a 1.5% hospitalization rate; COVID-19 has a low estimate of 10%.
